# Windows Boot Process

---

## Step 1: Power ON

Same as Linux.

---

## Step 2: BIOS/UEFI

Performs hardware initialization and POST.

---

## Step 3: Windows Boot Manager

Files:

```text
bootmgr
```

or

```text
bootmgfw.efi
```

Responsibilities:

- Read Boot Configuration Data (BCD)
- Select operating system

---

## Step 4: Boot Configuration Data (BCD)

Stores:

- Windows versions
- Recovery options
- Boot settings

Equivalent to GRUB configuration in Linux.

---

## Step 5: winload.exe

Loads:

### Windows Kernel

```text
ntoskrnl.exe
```

Also loads:

- HAL (Hardware Abstraction Layer)
- Drivers
- Registry

---

## Step 6: Kernel Initialization

Kernel initializes:

- Memory manager
- Scheduler
- Process manager
- Device manager

---

## Step 7: Session Manager

Process:

```text
smss.exe
```

Creates:

```text
csrss.exe
wininit.exe
```

---

## Step 8: Service Control Manager

Process:

```text
services.exe
```

Starts:

- Networking
- Event logs
- Windows Defender
- Update services

---

## Step 9: Login Process

Process:

```text
winlogon.exe
```

Displays:

```text
Ctrl + Alt + Del
```

or login screen.

---

## Step 10: Explorer Starts

Process:

```text
explorer.exe
```

Loads:

- Desktop
- Start Menu
- Taskbar

System becomes ready.

---

# Windows Boot Process Diagram

```text
Power ON
    ↓
BIOS/UEFI
    ↓
POST
    ↓
Boot Manager
    ↓
BCD
    ↓
winload.exe
    ↓
ntoskrnl.exe
    ↓
smss.exe
    ↓
services.exe
    ↓
winlogon.exe
    ↓
explorer.exe
```

---

# Linux vs Windows Boot Process

| Linux | Windows |
|---------|---------|
| GRUB | Boot Manager |
| Kernel | ntoskrnl.exe |
| systemd | services.exe |
| initramfs | winload.exe |
| PID 1 | Session Manager |
| Targets | Explorer/Desktop |

---

# Useful Linux Commands

### View Kernel Version

```bash
uname -r
```

### View PID 1

```bash
ps -p 1
```

### Boot Time Analysis

```bash
systemd-analyze
```

### List Services

```bash
systemctl list-units --type=service
```

### View Boot Logs

```bash
journalctl -b
```

